detail_description: Cerro San Bernardo, also known as San Bernardo Mountain, offers breathtaking panoramic views of Salta City. Visitors can choose to hike or run up more than 1,000 steps to the summit or take a cable car from Parque San Martin for an easier ascent. At the top, there's a restaurant, a landscaped garden, and a small artisanal market where you can find souvenirs.
name: Cerro San Bernardo

excerpt: Salta is a provincial capital in mountainous northwestern Argentina. Founded in 1582, it’s known for its Spanish colonial architecture and Andean heritage. The city centers on Plaza 9 de Julio, an elegant, cafe-lined square bordered by the neoclassical Salta Cathedral and El Cabildo, an 18th-century town hall turned historical museum. Museo de Arqueología de Alta Montaña (MAAM) nearby houses Incan artifacts.
detail_description: Salta, a charming provincial capital in the mountainous northwest of Argentina, boasts a rich history dating back to 1582. The city is renowned for its well-preserved Spanish colonial architecture and strong Andean cultural heritage. Visitors are drawn to Plaza 9 de Julio, an elegant square lined with cafes and bordered by the neoclassical Salta Cathedral and El Cabildo, which now serves as a historical museum.
name: Salta

detail_description: Embark on an unforgettable journey through the stunning landscapes of Salta by hopping on the Tren a las Nubes, also known as the Train to the Clouds. Departing from Salta's central station, this iconic train ascends to Quebrada del Toro, reaching heights that often take it through the clouds. The breathtaking route culminates at an impressive 13,845 feet above sea level.
name: Tren a las Nubes
address: Planta Baja Local 33 Galería Baccaro, A4400 Salta, Argentina

excerpt: Refined Spanish colonial-style Franciscan basilica, convent & National Historical Monument.
detail_description: IGLESIA Y MUSEO SAN FRANCISCO is a stunning Spanish colonial-style basilica and convent located in Salta, Argentina. This historical monument, built between 1767 and 1872, showcases Italianate Neocolonial architecture with ivory-white columns against vibrant ox-blood walls. The church's intricate detailing of Latin inscriptions and Neoclassical patterns adds to its grandeur.
name: Basílica Menor y Convento de San Francisco en Salta

detail_description: Plaza 9 de Julio is a vibrant and historic square located in the heart of Salta, Argentina. This iconic plaza serves as a central gathering place for locals and visitors alike, surrounded by stunning colonial architecture that reflects the rich cultural heritage of the region. The lush greenery and well-maintained gardens provide a serene atmosphere, perfect for leisurely strolls or simply soaking in the lively ambiance.
name: plaza 9 de julio
address: Martina Silva de Gurruchaga 115, A4408 Salta, Argentina

excerpt: Archaeology museum housing the Mummies of Llullaillaco & other exhibits in a 19th-century building.
detail_description: The Museum of High Altitude Archaeology (MAAM) is located in a 19th-century building and showcases artifacts from the Inca culture found in the Andes Mountains. One of its most famous exhibits is the Mummies of Llullaillaco, which were discovered at a high altitude near the peak of Llullaillaco. This significant archaeological find dates back over 500 years and provides insight into Inca rituals and practices.
name: Museum of High Altitude Archaeology

detail_description: Convento San Bernardo is a historic 16th-century Neo-classical monument located in Salta, Argentina. This beautiful building once served as a chapel and hospital and now houses an order of Carmelite nuns. While visitors are not allowed inside the adobe building, it's worth admiring its exterior, including the impressive wooden door crafted by indigenous artisans in 1762. If you're lucky, you may even have the chance to purchase homemade pastries from the nuns outside.
name: Convento San Bernardo

detail_description: Plaza 9 de Julio serves as the bustling heart of the city, attracting locals and visitors alike as a popular meeting spot. The main square is adorned with numerous palm trees and features a prominent monument of General Arenales, a revered figure known for his involvement in various wars. This central plaza stands as a significant landmark in the city's landscape.
name: Plaza 9 de julio
address: Dr. Luis Güemes 629, A4400 Salta, Argentina

excerpt: Roman Catholic cathedral dating to the 1800s, with an ornate pink facade & a gilded interior.
detail_description: Catedral Basílica de Salta is a stunning Roman Catholic cathedral with a striking pink facade and an opulent gilded interior. It was designated as a National Historic Monument in 1941 and holds great significance as the resting place of General Guemes, a national hero who played a crucial role in Argentina's fight for independence.
name: Catedral Basílica de Salta

detail_description: San Bernardo's Hill, also known as Cerro San Bernardo, is a popular spot in Salta for outdoor activities and relaxation. It offers stunning panoramic views of the city from its summit, which can be reached by climbing over 1,000 steps or taking a cable car from Parque San Martin. At the top, visitors can enjoy a restaurant with gourmet dining options and explore beautiful gardens.
name: San Bernardo's Hill
address: Cam. Cerro San Bernardo, A4400 Salta, Argentina

detail_description: Balcarce is a charming street located near the railway station, known for its vibrant traditional folk music scene. It's the perfect place to immerse yourself in the local culture and enjoy a lively pena experience.
name: Balcarce

detail_description: Doña Salta is a must-visit for those interested in exploring the rich history and culture of Salta, Argentina. The city's museums, such as the Museum of Fine Arts and Museo Guemes, offer an immersive experience into the region's significance in Argentine history. Visitors can learn about Martin Miguel de Guemes, a local hero of the Argentine War of Independence, through interactive exhibits and talking portraits.
name: Doña Salta

excerpt: Blue & pink pastels color the facade, bell tower & interiors of this Italian-style church from 1873.
detail_description: Iglesia la Viña, Parroquia Ntra. Sra. de la Candelaria is a stunning Italian-style church dating back to 1873, located in Salta. The exterior is adorned with blue and pink pastels, reflecting the traditional colors of the region. Inside, visitors can admire intricate paintings on the walls and ceilings.
name: Iglesia la Viña, Parroquia Ntra. Sra. de la Candelaria

detail_description: The Monument General Martin Miguel de Guemes, located at the base of San Bernardo Hill in a charming neighborhood of Salta, pays tribute to an Argentine independence hero and former governor. Erected in 1931 on the spot where he fell in battle, it offers a historical and picturesque setting. The surrounding park is popular with locals and provides a great view of the city, especially at sunset.
name: Monument General Martin Miguel de Guemes

excerpt: Museum in a restored mansion featuring South American art from the 1700s to the contemporary era.
detail_description: The Museum of Fine Arts in Salta, Argentina is housed in a restored mansion and showcases South American art spanning from the 1700s to contemporary works. The collection includes paintings by local, regional, and national artists. The museum features contemporary art on the ground floor and works from other eras on the first floor, including religious art and ceramics. Visitors can also explore shops selling souvenirs and enjoy cafes nearby.
name: Museum of Fine Arts in Salta, Argentina

excerpt: Food marketplace in a historical building, known for its produce, nuts, cheeses & condiments.
detail_description: Mercado Municipal San Miguel is a historical food marketplace offering a wide variety of local produce, nuts, cheeses, and condiments. It's not just a place to shop but also an excellent spot for dining on typical Argentinian empanadas and pizza, as well as fresh fruits and vegetables. Located near Plaza 9 de Julio, the lower floor features a typical market while upstairs houses numerous restaurants and food stands.
name: Mercado Municipal San Miguel
address: Av. San Martín 780, A4400 Salta, Argentina

excerpt: Park featuring a palm-fringed lake with pedal boats, plus a statue of statesman José de San Martín.
detail_description: San Martin Park in Salta is a picturesque destination featuring a palm-fringed lake where visitors can enjoy pedal boating. The park also boasts a statue of the revered statesman José de San Martín, adding to its historical charm. Additionally, the park is conveniently located near the bus terminal, making it easily accessible for travelers arriving or departing from Salta. Visitors can take leisurely walks through the large grove and admire various monuments while enjoying the serene surroundings.
name: San Martin Park
address: Av. San Martín 27, A4400 Salta, Argentina

detail_description: As of 2024, it has been reported that the road from San Antonio de los Cobres to Cachi is unsafe due to a bridge being out. Travelers are advised against driving this route until further notice. If you have information about the safety of this road in the future, please share your experience.
name: Pje. San Carlos

detail_description: San Lorenzo, a neighboring town, offers a picturesque drive and a glimpse into its history as a summer retreat for the aristocracy. Following Napoleon's invasion of Spain, wealthy Spaniards sought refuge in Argentina, bringing their riches with them. As a result, San Lorenzo boasts visible signs of opulence from this era.
name: San Lorenzo

detail_description: The Parroquia de Nuestra Señora del Rosario, located in Humahuaca, is a charming and picturesque religious institution with a rich history dating back to 1641. Inside, visitors can admire the image of the town's patrons, San Antonio and la Virgen de la Candelaria, as well as oil paintings by Marcos Sapaca from the Cuzco school.
name: Parroquia de Nuestra Señora del Rosario

detail_description: Patio De La Empanada, located at the corner of San Martin and Esteco, is a must-visit spot in Salta for those looking to savor the best empanadas. This open-air patio features several family-run stalls offering classic Salteno fare, with each stall serving its own version of the iconic stuffed baked pastries. The variety of recipes from different vendors makes it worth trying multiple empanadas to notice the subtle differences in flavors.
name: Patio De La Empanada

excerpt: Multimedia displays, interactive exhibits & artifacts from Güemes' life & the War of Independence.
detail_description: The Guemes Museum offers a captivating journey through the life of General Martin Miguel de Guemes and the War of Independence. With multimedia displays, interactive exhibits, and artifacts, visitors can explore ten rooms covering key milestones in Guemes' life and his role in historical events such as the defense against English invasions and his governance of Salta. The museum provides a modern and immersive experience with hidden TV screens in the traditional house, offering a complete tour lasting approximately 45 minutes to an hour.
name: Guemes Museum

detail_description: If you're planning a visit to Salta, make sure to include the Teleférico San Bernardo in your itinerary. This charming cable car takes you on an exhilarating ride up to a hill that offers stunning panoramic views of the city and its surroundings. Tickets can be conveniently purchased at the base for around 2200 pesos for a round trip, with minimal wait times typically under ten minutes. As you ascend, you'll be treated to beautiful sights of palm trees and gardens, making the journey itself quite enjoyable.
name: Teleférico San Bernardo
address: Av. San Martín 4400, A4400 Salta, Argentina

excerpt: Dramatic forest reserve in mountain foothills usually shrouded in mist, with lichens & orchids.
detail_description: Quebrada de San Lorenzo is a dramatic forest reserve located just 10 kilometers from the city center, offering a perfect escape into nature. The reserve boasts lush yungas vegetation with abundant ferns, lichens, orchids, and other epiphytes. Visitors can enjoy bird watching while walking the well-marked trails through the exuberant forest. The area is known for its special magic that attracts all who visit it, with the San Lorenzo River adding to its charm.
name: San Lorenzo Ravine
address: A4401 Villa San Lorenzo, Salta, Argentina

detail_description: The Monumento 20 de Febrero is a significant stop on the city tour, paying tribute to the battle of Salta in Plaza Armada Argentina. Visitors can take a half-hour break at the nearby handicraft market, offering an array of trinkets, textiles, and Andean souvenirs. It's a family-friendly spot with a good playground for kids to enjoy.
name: 20 de Febrero Monument

detail_description: Located just a block away from the cathedral, Museo de Arte Contemporáneo in Salta, Argentina is housed in a magnificent three-storey Italian-style building dating back to the 19th century. Originally built for a wealthy local family, the bottom floor was used for commerce, the middle for the family, and the top for their servants. Today, it stands as a stunning museum showcasing contemporary art and is definitely worth a visit when exploring Salta.
name: Museo de Arte Contemporáneo - Salta, Argentina

detail_description: La Casona del Molino is a charming colonial house from the 18th century known as 'La pena de los salteos.' Here, local musicians gather every night to play classic folk melodies. Unlike other venues in the city, La Casona offers a unique experience where musicians share drinks and play music in its spacious rooms with adobe walls and antique decor. The atmosphere feels like friends playing at home.
name: La Casona del Molino
address: Cnel, Luis Burela 1, A4400 Salta, Argentina

excerpt: Dinner-show club serving Andean cuisine, plus nightly traditional folk music & dance performances.
detail_description: Peña La Vieja Estación is a renowned dinner-show club in Salta, Argentina, offering an authentic Andean dining experience accompanied by traditional folk music and dance performances. Located in the heart of the bustling Balcarce area, it stands out as one of the pioneering venues in the region. The establishment seamlessly blends traditional folklore with high-quality gastronomy, creating an immersive cultural experience for visitors.
name: PEÑA LA VIEJA ESTACION

detail_description: Embark on an extraordinary adventure through the rugged terrain of Northern Argentina with the Safari To The Clouds tour. Experience the thrill of traversing the challenging landscape in an all-terrain vehicle and embark on a unique journey aboard the Train to the Clouds. Traverse the stunning Quebrada del Toro until you reach San Antonio de los Cobres, immersing yourself in the breathtaking natural beauty and rich cultural heritage along the way.
name: Safari To The Clouds

detail_description: When visiting Humahuaca, it is recommended to explore the Iglesia Candelaria, which boasts its antiquity dating back to 1641. Inside the church, you can find an image of the town's patrons (San Antonio and la Virgen de la Candelaria) as well as remarkable oil paintings by Marcos Sapaca from the Cuzco school.
name: Ojos de Mar Apart

excerpt: Individually decorated quarters in a relaxed hotel featuring a warm restaurant & a breakfast buffet.
detail_description: Hotel Salta is a charming 4-star hotel situated in the heart of Salta, offering individually decorated rooms and modern amenities such as free Wi-Fi, air conditioning, and a mini-bar. The hotel features a warm restaurant serving a breakfast buffet and boasts very good user ratings for its location, cleanliness, and overall experience. Guests can enjoy the full-service spa, outdoor pool, fitness center, and panoramic views from the on-site restaurant.
name: Hotel Salta
address: Buenos Aires Nº1, A4400 Salta, Argentina

excerpt: Small, leafy green space honoring a 19th-century military leader & the site of a weekly craft fair.
name: Plaza Gral. Don Martin Miguel de Guemes

detail_description: Plaza de la Democracia (Tribunales) is a very clean and pleasant square, perfect for leisurely strolls and relaxation. It offers a tranquil atmosphere and features panic button posts for added safety. The architecture and history of Salta are beautifully showcased here, making it an ideal spot to visit. Additionally, visitors can charge their cell phones using solar energy at the plaza. Many people also use the space to practice choreography, adding a lively touch to this nice and calm place.
name: Plaza de la Democracia (Tribunales)

excerpt: Cable car to a lookout point with panoramic city views, landscaped fountains & forest trails.
name: Teleférico San Bernardo
address: Av. San Martín 4400, A4400 Salta, Argentina

name: Adobe Cocina Regional
address: Caseros 511 Primer Piso, A4400 Salta, Argentina

detail_description: El Club de la Milanesa offers an outstanding selection of delicious breaded meat dishes, with generous portions and a friendly staff. It is the perfect destination for enthusiasts of this popular Argentinean dish. The ambiance is pleasant, although some might find the music too loud, making it challenging to have conversations. However, there are lighter options available on the menu besides milanesa with fries, ensuring that everyone can find something to suit their taste.
name: El Club de la Milanesa

detail_description: When in Humahuaca, it is recommended to visit the Iglesia Candelaria due to its ancient origins dating back to 1641. Inside, you will find an image of the town's patrons (San Antonio and la Virgen de la Candelaria) as well as oil paintings by Marcos Sapaca, a painter from the Cuzco school. Opposite the church stands the town hall, renowned for its clock tower.
name: Cono de Arita Apart

detail_description: Salta La Linda, also known as Salta the Beautiful, is a charming city in northwestern Argentina with well-preserved colonial architecture and a warm climate year-round. Nestled in the Andes foothills, it offers stunning mountain views and a tranquil pace of life where siestas are still observed. Visitors can enjoy guided city tours to explore its historic buildings and churches.
name: Salta La Linda

detail_description: Caseros Street in Salta is the go-to place for travelers looking to explore adventure sports and unique experiences outside the city. This pedestrian street is lined with travel agencies offering deals on activities like river rafting, mountain biking, trekking, and 4x4 tours. It's highly recommended to visit this area if you're seeking thrilling outdoor adventures beyond Salta.
name: Caseros

detail_description: Pje. Molinos is a small, sun-drenched adobe village that serves as a picturesque stop on a road trip through the diverse landscapes of northwestern Argentina. Starting from the sophisticated city of Salta, travelers can embark on a 3-day journey that takes them through farmland, jungle, and high desert before reaching this charming destination.
name: Pje. Molinos

detail_description: Alfajores are a popular confectionery found in Argentina and across South America. These delightful treats come in various types, with the most prevalent being filled with dulce de leche, encased in coconut shavings, and nestled between two buttery cookies.
name: Alfajores

detail_description: Corsodromo Salta-Avda. del Carnaval is a popular spot in Salta, especially during the Carnaval weekend. Visitors have expressed their admiration for the beauty and charm of this place, with some expressing a desire to return multiple times. The Corsodromo seems to be a vibrant and lively location, although it may not be as active during certain times such as the Carnaval weekend when many establishments are closed.
name: Corsodromo Salta-Avda. del Carnaval
address: Av. John Fitzerald Kennedy, A4400 Salta, Argentina

detail_description: Market Salta, the first handicraft market in Argentina, has been operating since 1968 in a historic colonial mansion from the 18th century. Visitors can explore a diverse range of craft products including basketry, weavings, pottery, silverware, wrought iron and leather works, musical instruments, as well as high-quality regional foodstuffs and wines. Additionally, it's recommended to use Passporter for trip organization.
name: Market Salta

detail_description: San Bernardo Cable Car Station in Salta is a must-see attraction that takes you to the top of San Bernardo hill, offering stunning views of the city. The area around the cable car complex provides opportunities for various activities or simply relaxing amidst lush vegetation. It's an ideal spot to witness breathtaking sunsets. Visitors recommend walking up the stairs and enjoying the panoramic view, making it an excellent experience not to be missed.
name: San Bernardo Cable Car Station

detail_description: Los Andes, located in the northwest region of Argentina, is characterized by its close proximity to the Andes and Bolivia. This has contributed to the prevalence of indigenous and rural cultures, offering a stark contrast to the Europeanized urban centers found elsewhere in the country. The area was historically inhabited by various indigenous groups, including the Diaguita-Calchaqui people, and today it is not uncommon to come across Quechan communities while exploring the region.
name: Los Andes

detail_description: La Puna, located in the northwest of Argentina, offers a unique travel experience. The train journey from Salta to La Polvorilla Viaduct is an extraordinary adventure, covering 135 miles and reaching a height of 13,845 feet above sea level. This makes it one of the highest train journeys globally, providing breathtaking views of the Andes.
name: La Puna, Tourisme dans le nord-ouest argentin
